Within-session loss-chasing

Losses can be chased within a gambling session. In this set of analyses we assess within-session loss-chasing via - 1.) persistence which refers to continuation of gambling in the face of losses, 2.)increasing stake amount following losses and 3.) increasing speed of play (i.e., post loss speeding) following losses.

# load data
descriptives_df <- read_csv(here("data", "processed_data","EDA", "Within_session", "descriptives_df.csv"))

Combine in one table

# in the manuscript, we present all information in one table
# here we combine the separate tables into one
one_table <- rbind(num_round_comp, stake_comp, win_comp, loss_comp, total_spent_comp)

# for brevity, we do not report results on maximum and minimum
one_table <- one_table %>%
  filter(!comp %in% c("Maximum stake", "Minimum stake", "Maximum win",
                      "Minimum win", "Maximum loss", "Minimum loss"))

# correct the p values for multiple comparisons
one_table$p <- p.adjust(one_table$pt, method = "holm")

# format the table
one_table <- one_table %>%
  mutate(
    # rename comp into Parameter
    Parameter = comp,
    # for these variables, keep 1 digit after the decimal point
    across(c(mean_x:t, logBF), ~round(.x, digits = 1)),
    # for effect size g, keep 3 digits after the decimal point
    g = round(g, digits = 3),
    # report p values below .001 as < .001
    p = ifelse(p < .001, "<.001", sprintf("%.3f", round(p, digits = 3))),
    # combine mean and standard deviation for each group
    `High-involvement` = paste0(mean_x, " (", sd_x, ")"),
    `Low-involvement` = paste0(mean_y, " (", sd_y, ")")
    ) %>%
  # delete some redundant variables
  select(-c(comp:sd_y), -pt, -pw, -d, -BF) %>%
  select(Parameter, `High-involvement`, `Low-involvement`, diff, lowerCI, upperCI, df, t, p, logBF, g)

# produce the APA tables for publication
table_final_play_beh <- rempsyc::nice_table(one_table ,

Persistance - Probability to quit

Players can chase losses (or wins) by persisting in the face of losses. This is commonly referred to as persistence or continuation in the loss-chasing literature. In this study we operationalize persistence/continuation as the probability of quitting following losses or wins incurred in the previous round. We assess this across outcome streaks and in doing so assess the following research question:Do players chase losses high- (low) players have a higher (lower) probability to quit following losses (wins) across the varying streak lengths of 1, 2 or >2 losses (wins)?

quit_df <- read_csv(here("data", "processed_data","EDA", "Within_session", "quit_df.csv"))

Relative Likelihood of Quitting

In this section we assess the probability of quitting among high- and low-involvement players across the loss and win outcomes across the 3 streak length categories. We first compute the relative likelihood of quitting the gamble by dividing the probability to quit following losses (wins) across each streak length by the overall probability to quit for each player. We control for the overall probability of quitting here because the high-involvement players overall have a higher tendency of

# calculate the relative likelihood of quitting
quit_df <-quit_df %>%
  mutate(quit_prob_relative = quit_prob_outcome/quit_prob_overall)

Mixed ANOVA Model: Relative P(Quit)

quit_anova <- aov_ez(id = "player_id",
                        dv = "quit_prob_relative",
                        between = "group_levels",
                        within = c("curr_streak_len","outcome"),
                        data = quit_df,
                        na.rm = TRUE)
quit_anova_table <- nice(quit_anova)

# format the anova table
quit_anova_table <- quit_anova_table%>%
  mutate(
    Parameter = "Relative likelihood to quit (%)",
    Effect = c("Involvement level", "Streak Length","Interaction: Involvement level * Streak length", 
               "Outcome", "Interaction: Involvement level * Outcome", 
               "Interaction: Streak length * Outcome" ,
               "Interaction: Involvement level * Streak length * Outcome"),
    # remove asterisks from the F values
    `F` = str_remove_all(`F`, "[*]"),
    # remove white space
    `F` = str_trim(`F`),
    p = `p.value`
  ) %>%
  #select(Parameter, Effect, df, MSE, `F`, ges, p)
  select(Effect, df, MSE, `F`, ges, p)

Plot - Relative P(Quit)

quit_prob_summary <- quit_df %>%
  # use euro cents instead of euros as the unit
  group_by(group_levels) %>%
  group_modify(~Rmisc::summarySEwithin(.x, 
                                       measurevar = "quit_prob_relative", 
                                       idvar = "player_id",
                                       withinvars = c("outcome", "curr_streak_len"))) %>%
  mutate(
    curr_streak_len = factor(curr_streak_len, levels = c("1", "2", ">2"),
                   labels = c("1", "2", ">2"))
  )%>%
  ungroup()
quit_plot <- quit_prob_summary %>%
  group_by(group_levels)%>%
  ggplot(aes(curr_streak_len, quit_prob_relative, 
              color = outcome, shape = outcome)) +
  geom_point(position = position_dodge(width = dodge_width), size = shape_size) +

Pairwise comparison: Relative P(Quit)

Next we will conduct 4 bonferroni-correct post-hoc t-test pairwise comparisons. In the first paired t-tests we will compare the relative likelihood i.e., probability to quit across each current round outcome and streak lengths:

Paired t-test: * High-loss vs. High-win_ streak_len_1 * High-loss vs. High-win_ streak_len_2 * High-loss vs. High-win_ streak_len_grt_2 * Low-loss vs. Low-win_ streak_len_1 * Low-loss vs. Low-win_ streak_len_2 * Low-loss vs. Low-win_ streak_len_grt_2

Independent t-test: In the independent group comparison we will compare the two groups - high- and low-involvement groups across each prior outcome and streak lengths and the difference of differences as well.

  • High-loss vs. Low-loss_ streak_len_1
  • High-loss vs. Low-loss_ streak_len_2
  • High-loss vs. Low-loss_ streak_len_grt_2
  • High-win vs. Low-win_ streak_len_1
  • High-win vs. Low-win_ streak_len_2
  • High-win vs. Low-win_ streak_len_grt_2
  • (High-Loss - High-Win) vs. (Low-Loss - Low-Win)_streak_len_1
  • (High-Loss - High-Win) vs. (Low-Loss - Low-Win)_streak_len_2
  • (High-Loss - High-Win) vs. (Low-Loss - Low-Win)_streak_len_grt_2
# Format the table

quit_wide <- quit_df%>%
  pivot_wider(id_cols = c(group_levels, player_id, curr_streak_len),
              names_from = outcome,
              values_from = quit_prob_relative)%>% 
  mutate(diff_mean = loss - win)


## PAIRED T-TEST

# within-group comparison

comp_within <- quit_wide %>%
  group_by(group_levels, curr_streak_len)%>%
  group_modify(~TES(.x$loss, .x$win, paired = TRUE))%>%
  mutate(d = dz, g = gav)%>%
  ungroup() %>%
  select(-group_levels, -dz, -gav, -dav)


comp_within_table <- comp_within%>%
  mutate(

                   "High-Loss vs. High-Win",
                   "High-Loss vs. High-Win",
                   "Low-Loss vs. Low-Win",
                   "Low-Loss vs. Low-Win",
                   "Low-Loss vs. Low-Win"),

                              "1", "2", ">2")
    ,pt = p.adjust(pt, method = "holm"))

  mutate(
    across(mean_x:upperCI, ~round(.x, digits = 3)),
    across(c(d,g), ~round(.x, digits = 3)),
    t = round(t, digits = 1),
    df = round(df, digits = 1),
    p = ifelse(pt <.001, "<.001", sprintf("%.3f", round(pt, digits = 3))),
    logBF = round(logBF, digits = 2)
  )%>%
  select(Comparison_group, Comparison_streak_len, mean_x:t, p, logBF, g)

#Stake Amount change

Players may chase losses by increasing their stake sizes following losses. In this set of analyses we aim to assess if players chase losses by increasing stake amount following incurring sequential losses (wins) of streak lengths 1, 2 and >2 and do we observe systematic differences across high- and low-involvement players?

# load data
stake_change_df <- read_csv(here("data", "processed_data","EDA", "Within_session", "stake_change_df.csv"))

Stake size change overall basic info

Here we check the total number of players across the involvement levels, the total number of rounds, the mean, SD, minimum and maximum number of rounds in the quit probability dataset.

# number of players in the stakes df
n_players <- stake_change_df %>%

n_round <- stake_change_df %>%

            mean_rounds = mean(n_round),
            sd_rounds = sd(n_round),
            min_rounds = min(n_round),
            max_rounds = max(n_round))

Players can chase their losses by increasing stake sizes following losses. In this script we will analyse if players increase their stakes following losses and wins across varying streak lengths of - 1.) 1, 2.) 2 and 3.) >2 streak length. We will run a mixed anova model (2 x 2 x 3 design) in which the between-group factor is group levels (high- and low-involvement) and the within-group factors is a.) previous round outcome and b.) streak length. The dependent variable here is the overall mean stake size change.

Mixed ANOVA Model - Stake amount change

stake_change_anova <- aov_ez(id = "player_id",
                        dv = "stake_change_size_overall",
                        between = "group_levels",
                        within = c("prev_streak_len","prev_outcome"),
                        data = stake_change_df,
                        na.rm = TRUE)

Pairwise comparison - Stake change overall

Next we will conduct 4 bonferroni-correct post-hoc t-test pairwise comparisons. In the first paired t-tests we will compare the overall mean stake size change across each prior outcome and streak lengths:

Paired t-test: * High-loss vs. High-win_ streak_len_1 * High-loss vs. High-win_ streak_len_2 * High-loss vs. High-win_ streak_len_grt_2 * Low-loss vs. Low-win_ streak_len_1 * Low-loss vs. Low-win_ streak_len_2 * Low-loss vs. Low-win_ streak_len_grt_2

Independent t-test: In the independent group comparison we will compare the two groups - high- and low-involvement groups across each prior outcome and streak lengths and the difference of differences as well.

  • High-loss vs. Low-loss_ streak_len_1
  • High-loss vs. Low-loss_ streak_len_2
  • High-loss vs. Low-loss_ streak_len_grt_2
  • High-win vs. Low-win_ streak_len_1
  • High-win vs. Low-win_ streak_len_2
  • High-win vs. Low-win_ streak_len_grt_2
  • (High-Loss - High-Win) vs. (Low-Loss - Low-Win)_streak_len_1
  • (High-Loss - High-Win) vs. (Low-Loss - Low-Win)_streak_len_2
  • (High-Loss - High-Win) vs. (Low-Loss - Low-Win)_streak_len_grt_2

stake_change_size_overall_wide <- stake_change_df%>%
  pivot_wider(id_cols = c(group_levels, player_id, prev_streak_len),
              names_from = prev_outcome,
              values_from = stake_change_size_overall)%>% 
  mutate(diff_mean = loss - win)


## PAIRED T-TEST

# within-group comparison

comp_within <- stake_change_size_overall_wide %>%
  group_by(group_levels, prev_streak_len)%>%
  group_modify(~TES(.x$loss, .x$win, paired = TRUE))%>%
  mutate(d = dz, g = gav)%>%
  ungroup() %>%
  select(-group_levels, -dz, -gav, -dav)


comp_within_table <- comp_within%>%
  mutate(
    Comparison_group = c("High-Loss vs. High-Win",
                   "High-Loss vs. High-Win",
                   "High-Loss vs. High-Win",
                   "Low-Loss vs. Low-Win",
                   "Low-Loss vs. Low-Win",
                   "Low-Loss vs. Low-Win"),
    Comparison_streak_len = c("1", "2", ">2",
                              "1", "2", ">2")
    ,pt = p.adjust(pt, method = "holm"))

comp_within_table <- comp_within_table%>%
  mutate(
    across(mean_x:upperCI, ~round(.x, digits = 3)),
    across(c(d,g), ~round(.x, digits = 3)),
    t = round(t, digits = 1),
    df = round(df, digits = 1),
    p = ifelse(pt <.001, "<.001", sprintf("%.3f", round(pt, digits = 3))),
    logBF = round(logBF, digits = 2)
  )%>%
  select(Comparison_group, Comparison_streak_len, mean_x:t, p, logBF, g)

Pairwise comparison: Stake change probability

Next we will conduct 4 bonferroni-correct post-hoc t-test pairwise comparisons. In the paired t-tests we will compare the overall mean probability of changing stake sizes across each prior outcome and streak lengths:

Paired t-test: * High-loss vs. High-win_ streak_len_1 * High-loss vs. High-win_ streak_len_2 * High-loss vs. High-win_ streak_len_grt_2 * Low-loss vs. Low-win_ streak_len_1 * Low-loss vs. Low-win_ streak_len_2 * Low-loss vs. Low-win_ streak_len_grt_2

Independent t-test: In the independent group comparison we will compare the two groups - high- and low-involvement groups across each prior outcome and streak lengths and the difference of differences as well.

  • High-loss vs. Low-loss_ streak_len_1
  • High-loss vs. Low-loss_ streak_len_2
  • High-loss vs. Low-loss_ streak_len_grt_2
  • High-win vs. Low-win_ streak_len_1
  • High-win vs. Low-win_ streak_len_2
  • High-win vs. Low-win_ streak_len_grt_2
  • (High-Loss - High-Win) vs. (Low-Loss - Low-Win)_streak_len_1
  • (High-Loss - High-Win) vs. (Low-Loss - Low-Win)_streak_len_2
  • (High-Loss - High-Win) vs. (Low-Loss - Low-Win)_streak_len_grt_2
# Format the table

stake_change_prob_wide <- stake_change_df%>%
  pivot_wider(id_cols = c(group_levels, player_id, prev_streak_len),
              names_from = prev_outcome,
              values_from = stake_change_prop)%>% 
  mutate(diff_mean = loss - win)


## PAIRED T-TEST

# within-group comparison

comp_within_prob <- stake_change_prob_wide %>%
  group_by(group_levels, prev_streak_len)%>%
  group_modify(~TES(.x$loss, .x$win, paired = TRUE))%>%
  mutate(d = dz, g = gav)%>%
  ungroup() %>%
  select(-group_levels, -dz, -gav, -dav)


comp_within_prob_table <- comp_within_prob%>%
  mutate(
    Comparison_group = c("High-Loss vs. High-Win",
                   "High-Loss vs. High-Win",
                   "High-Loss vs. High-Win",
                   "Low-Loss vs. Low-Win",
                   "Low-Loss vs. Low-Win",
                   "Low-Loss vs. Low-Win"),
    Comparison_streak_len = c("1", "2", ">2",
                              "1", "2", ">2")
    ,pt = p.adjust(pt, method = "holm"))

comp_within_prob_table <- comp_within_prob_table%>%
  mutate(
    across(mean_x:upperCI, ~round(.x, digits = 3)),
    across(c(d,g), ~round(.x, digits = 3)),
    t = round(t, digits = 1),
    df = round(df, digits = 1),
    p = ifelse(pt <.001, "<.001", sprintf("%.3f", round(pt, digits = 3))),
    logBF = round(logBF, digits = 2)
  )%>%
  select(Comparison_group, Comparison_streak_len, mean_x:t, p, logBF, g)

Speed of Play

# load data
rt_df <- read_csv(here("data", "processed_data","EDA", "Within_session", "rt_df.csv"))

Players may chase losses by increasing the speed of playing following losses. In this script we will analyse if players increase their speed of play following losses and wins across varying streak lengths of - 1.) 1, 2.) 2 and 3.) >2 streak length. We will run a mixed anova model (2 x 2 x 3 design) in which the between-group factor is group levels (high- and low-involvement) and the within-group factors is a.) previous round outcome and b.) streak length. The dependent variable here is the overall mean z-transformed RT scores.

# number of players in the stakes df
n_players <- rt_df %>% 
  group_by(group_levels) %>%
  distinct(player_id) %>%
  count()

#info about number of rounds

n_round <- rt_df %>% 
  group_by(group_levels) %>%
  summarise(total_rounds = sum(n_round),
            mean_rounds = mean(n_round),
            sd_rounds = sd(n_round),
            min_rounds = min(n_round),
            max_rounds = max(n_round))

Pairwise comparison: Speed of Play (zRT)

Next we will conduct 4 bonferroni-correct post-hoc t-test pairwise comparisons. In the paired t-tests we will compare the overall mean z-transformed RT’s across each prior outcome and streak lengths:

Paired t-test: * High-loss vs. High-win_ streak_len_1 * High-loss vs. High-win_ streak_len_2 * High-loss vs. High-win_ streak_len_grt_2 * Low-loss vs. Low-win_ streak_len_1 * Low-loss vs. Low-win_ streak_len_2 * Low-loss vs. Low-win_ streak_len_grt_2

Independent t-test: In the independent group comparison we will compare the two groups - high- and low-involvement groups across each prior outcome and streak lengths and the difference of differences as well.

  • High-loss vs. Low-loss_ streak_len_1
  • High-loss vs. Low-loss_ streak_len_2
  • High-loss vs. Low-loss_ streak_len_grt_2
  • High-win vs. Low-win_ streak_len_1
  • High-win vs. Low-win_ streak_len_2
  • High-win vs. Low-win_ streak_len_grt_2
  • (High-Loss - High-Win) vs. (Low-Loss - Low-Win)_streak_len_1
  • (High-Loss - High-Win) vs. (Low-Loss - Low-Win)_streak_len_2
  • (High-Loss - High-Win) vs. (Low-Loss - Low-Win)_streak_len_grt_2
# Format the table

rt_z_wide <- rt_df%>%
  pivot_wider(id_cols = c(group_levels, player_id, prev_streak_len),
              names_from = prev_outcome,
              values_from = rt_z_mean)%>% 
  mutate(diff_mean = loss - win)


## PAIRED T-TEST

# within-group comparison

comp_within <- rt_z_wide %>%
  group_by(group_levels, prev_streak_len)%>%
  group_modify(~TES(.x$loss, .x$win, paired = TRUE))%>%
  mutate(d = dz, g = gav)%>%
  ungroup() %>%
  select(-group_levels, -dz, -gav, -dav)  


comp_within_table <- comp_within%>%
  mutate(
    Comparison_group = c("High-Loss vs. High-Win",
                   "High-Loss vs. High-Win",
                   "High-Loss vs. High-Win",
                   "Low-Loss vs. Low-Win",
                   "Low-Loss vs. Low-Win",
                   "Low-Loss vs. Low-Win"),
    Comparison_streak_len = c("1", "2", ">2",
                              "1", "2", ">2")
    ,pt = p.adjust(pt, method = "holm"))

comp_within_table <- comp_within_table%>%
  mutate(
    across(mean_x:upperCI, ~round(.x, digits = 3)),
    across(c(d,g), ~round(.x, digits = 3)),
    t = round(t, digits = 1),
    df = round(df, digits = 1),
    p = ifelse(pt <.001, "<.001", sprintf("%.3f", round(pt, digits = 3))),
    logBF = round(logBF, digits = 2)
  )%>%
  select(Comparison_group, Comparison_streak_len, mean_x:t, p, logBF, g)
